<h2 id="implementation">Implementation Best Practices</h2>

<div class="prose max-w-none">

<p>Successful time tracking implementation requires more than choosing the right software. Based on our contractor surveys, these practices increase adoption rates from 60% to 85%:</p>

<h3>Week 1: Setup and Testing</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Start with 2-3 technicians:</strong> Iron out workflows before full deployment</li>
<li><strong>Configure job codes:</strong> Match your existing service categories and billing codes</li>
<li><strong>Test GPS accuracy:</strong> Verify location tracking at your common job sites</li>
<li><strong>Set up integrations:</strong> Connect to QuickBooks or your payroll system</li>
</ul>

<h3>Week 2: Team Training</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>15-minute training sessions:</strong> Show clock-in/out process and job selection</li>
<li><strong>Address privacy concerns:</strong> Explain GPS usage and data policies</li>
<li><strong>Create quick reference cards:</strong> Laminated cards with key steps</li>
<li><strong>Set clear expectations:</strong> Define consequences for not tracking time</li>
</ul>

<h3>Week 3-4: Full Rollout</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Daily check-ins:</strong> Review timesheet completeness each morning</li>
<li><strong>Fix issues immediately:</strong> Don't let problems compound</li>
<li><strong>Celebrate early wins:</strong> Share payroll accuracy improvements with the team</li>
<li><strong>Monitor adoption rates:</strong> Target 80%+ usage within 2 weeks</li>
</ul>

<p>Companies that follow this staged approach see 25% fewer implementation issues and 40% faster time-to-value.</p>

</div>

